PW is a HTTP/HTTPS daemon

designed to be light and lightweight on dependencies, it has a few features beyond trivial file-servers considered a bare-minimum:

 HTTP(S)
 - controller mostly behaves similarly to protocols described in http://linkeddata.github.io/SoLiD/
 - WebID/X509-User-Certificate signin
 - uploads on PUT and POST (Container and HTML-<form> support) 
 - paging large-containers: summarization, Link headers, sorted-ranges, offsets/cursors
 - lazy indexing

 MIME-types
 - input: email, Atom/RSS feeds, chatlogs, text-files, CSV, Markdown, highlighted-code
 - output: Atom/RSS feeds and lynx/links/w3m-compatible HTML[1234]
 - MIME-convert betweeen all RDF.rb and above formats
 - content-type select: Accept header or name-extension (suffix) hints 

 FRAMEWORK
 - customize behaviour: bind lambdas to RDF-types
 - stored URIs are relative and late-bound. mount your data on any hostname, on HTTP or HTTPS and manage it with common filesystem tools (ln, git, rsync, NFS)

SRC git clone https://github.com/hallwaykid/pw.git ||
    git clone http://repo.or.cz/w/www.git


install ruby bundler libssl-dev libgit2-dev libxml2-dev libxslt1-dev pkg-config
     cd pw/ruby                # enter srcdir
     ./install                 # link src -> lib
     bundle install            # install ruby libraries
USE  cd ..                     # goto server-root. if elsewhere copy/link {css,js}/
     ln conf/server/Procfile . # select Rack-engine
     foreman start             # start HTTP/HTTPS daemons

repl$ irb -rww

listen on 80/443 || # $ setcap cap_net_bind_service=+ep $(realpath `which ruby`)
 >1024 (behind apache/nginx/lighttpd)

clean$ rm -rf cache index

